It COULD really show how evil a person can be and there's an infinite amount of stories you could tell in this context (cannibalism? HOSTEL-like torture palaces? text: Hmm...I was kinda expecting a sequel to Election Year. I had in mind a set-up where it takes place a year after the previous film on the anniversary of The Purge being officially being done away with.  Police officers thinking it's going to be just a normal night arrive at an assault in progress by someone in a purge mask, the officers ask why he is doing what he's doing, the guy say "because it's Purge night", and the officers respond by saying the Purge is no longer a thing which enrages the suspect to charge at them with a knife and the perp ends up getting gunned down.  Thinking this was an isolated incident, the officers are alarmed to hear via their police scanner that incidents like this are breaking out on a national scale with good fraction of the population engaging in murderous activity.  With law enforcement agencies across the country outnumbered and stretched for resources, the country is quickly enveloped in chaos.  From there the night follows the police as they break up and gun down Purgers legally since they are in fact criminals as well as face the darkness in their own hearts and resist the urge to Purge themselves amongst their fellow officers over complicated conflicts they have had with one another in the past.  The overarching theme here being even if the "The Purge" is gone, the "Purgers" will always remain because the darkness of man cannot, and has never been, contained by law.

text: Not bad... Not bad at all. Looking forward to seeing this movie. I've always found The Purge to be disturbing, but accurate in it's use of social and political commentary. Since 2016, the United States has been just one dire situation away from people Purging in the streets, or even all out Civil War. We have a delusional, ego-maniacal real estate conman, and legendary Reality TV star at the forefront being rallied on by all the degenerate Right Wingers; the hate groups, and religious cults, and people with a weird sexual fetish for guns and the 2nd Amendment running the entire shit show. Meanwhile, the Left side of things has gotten so sensitive and thin skinned regarding everything under the fucking sun, that America has become nothing more than a goddamn schoolyard. The Right Wingers are the bullies trying to take everybody's lunch money (health care and general Civil and Human Rights), and the Left are the weak kids that have cried and whined all they can and now they're tired of taking it, so they're finally going to stand up for themselves, and in return the "schoolyard bullies" are gonna come back for revenge and shoot up the fucking schoolyard with an AR-15. America is fucked. It's a shell of a country and The Purge shines a bight light on that in its own way.

text: TL:DW?  Fake news.  :)  The First Purge, as such, wasn't going to work.  Political people had to FORCE IT TO "WORK".  That's the literal content of this very trailer.  Implications that the movie won't, most likely, touch?  Stereotypes, tropes, memes, false equivalencies and "what-about-this" arguments ALL have to be created, and maintained, to some extent, by those with the power to do so.  It's not even racism, classism or implicit bias as such.  Voter frauds are _rare._  Welfare queens are _rare._  People in the Media and in Politics have to _work_ to make crime and violence from demographic minorities seem disproportionately common, because the literal statistics, the numbers of the population itself, either the absolute numbers of people or the percentages of the population, _are not on the side of the Media and politicians._  That's just math and what "being in the minority" means, there's literally less of you.  "The Purge", in setting, exists to fabricate forensics.  It exists to make guys like Ted Nugent seem like anything other than off-their-rocker fucking liars and cunts.  It exists to make one side "factually" as bad as the other, because without it, there wouldn't BE villains or criminals from one side anymore, beyond a certain demographic vanishing point.  In a world where, if the protests and counter-protests are any indication, the white nationalists and neo-Nazis outnumber so-called "anti-fascists" by 90 to 1, "The Purge" as such is needed to make both sides seem "plausibly equal".  Even though in the real world, there's NINETY white nationalists, white supremacists and neo-Nazis for every ONE anti-fascist.  "The Purge" exists to "justify" a psycho-social predator/prey or abuser/victim relationship between the right-wing (predator/abuser) and the left-wings (prey/victim) of the United States, years to decades after the Media no longer has any ability to mask or justify the truth and gross asymmetry of what's really going on.  Which is:  We now live in a nation where No Lives Matter, if a police officer so much as drops a crumb from his donut or breaks a single bead of sweat.  That's the recent Supreme Court decision that's come down.  It's enshrined: a monolithically white, buzzcut and paramilitary horde of police officers now have the enshrined "right" to hunt down and murder ANY citizen at ANY time for ANY reason, or indeed, NONE.  "The Purge" exists to explain why a society like that allows guys like this (Ted Nugent) to live, without just plain saying "We're goose-stepping White Nationalists now, and we say Rich Old Men and their Kept Rednecks (like Ted here) and Kept Immigrant Boys (like Ajit Pai) get Due Process, while no one else does, down to your children, your babies or your dogs.  And also, HA.  HA HA HA.  We get away with it every time, because WE ARE WHITE AND SAY SO."  So yeah, how does the movie make the point even more obvious?  This has to be the last one.

text: Well this isn't the first time the Purge has tackled issues of racism & classism. Cool to see they are dedicating a whole film to it, instead of a segment. Poverty follows racial lines, so its interesting to see the clash of wealthy whites, & historically oppressed Black & minority neighborhoods. It seems as though White politicians are using the military & some local gangs to increase the violence in these non-white neighborhoods, to make the purge system "work".    People in government abusing their power for a particular goal, at the detriment of undesirables.    I wonder if the use of "ex-military" in the story is a subtle hint to police brutality & police state militarization or the FBI/CIA's shady actions towards the Black Panther party & Civil Rights Movement.

text: Hey, Universal! I've got a story premise for the next Purge movie that'll make bank and actually be good. Hear me out:  The Purge 4 opens like a standard Purge movie with groups of poor and oppressed citizens fearing for what will happen to them at the murderous government hands that not-so-secretly control this yearly event. Now, enter Rick Sanchez with thousands of wardrobes of Iron Man-tier power armor for these groups along with the locations of all the New Founding Fathers and their backers.   The next 30-45 minutes plays out like a ultra-violent absurdist comedy. The Purge enthusiasts, government and modern society are swept up in a bloodbath that makes the French Revolution look like an after-school slap fight between two kindergartners. Rick then makes the message abundantly clear that this franchise's premise was inherently absurd and that no amount of gore effects and pseudo-intellectual social commentary could change that.  The ending scene is thousands of poor people in power armor having a dance-off on the blood and corpses of their oppressors to the tune of upbeat 90's hip hop.  Bam! Certified fresh on RT and guaranteed $100 million opening weekend. Your welcome.

text: These movies suck. The story is so lazy and haphazardly thrown together. The characters are extremely unconvincing and are impossible to care about while the filmmakers have made no attempt to rationalize why people would ever let something like this occur.  Even if there was a purge, why would all the people just run around trying to kill each other? I think there would be far more who would rob a bank, or steal cars from a dealership. People would be out to take the things they could not afford while the businesses would most likely have to hire armed guards to protect their merchandise. The sad thing is that the premise of this franchise is very interesting and full of potential but the makers behind the purge seem to be entirely incapable of utilizing that potential.

text: Tbh I think this is will be a good movie only people are looking at it through a wrong POV...I mean come on, We are all humans and we shouldn’t let our differences turn as against each other....we are all on earth for a reason, and I damn right sure that reason aint to kill and hurt other people. God loved us unconditionally even when he saw our flaws and we should do that too....it doesn’t matter if we are white, black, brown whatever we are all beautiful in our own way and we should have love in our hearts instead of hate. When I read some of these comments I was shocked tbh, “make white ppl the bad guys and the black the good guys” and there was a reply saying... “now you guys know how is black ppl have been marked as “thugs” and “criminals “..... and that one reply my heart broke...bcuz no matter what skin color, nationality, gender or religion we shouldn’t have to go through that point in life where ppl judge you by your looks....we shouldn’t have to go through being called “Ugly” “Fat” “Criminal”etc...just bcuz of our skin color or nationally or religion, We are all human beings for crying out loud...we should love each other and wish for the good to come in other ppl’s life’s...not wish death, harm, or anything bad on other people’s life bcuz of where there are from or hw they look....I for one think this movie shows how “purge” came to be....and that no matter what color we are we have hate inside us, and that we should stop that! One voice may not matter! But imagine if we all stood up for one another! We helped one another! Imagine a world where racism never existed imagine a world where countries never went at war with another! Imagine a world where we didn’t have to walk down streets and worry bout being raped or robbed! We could achieve that....if only we showed Love instead of Hate. I know a lot of u will reply and try to point out what I typed out wrong and what I said wrong...but guess what? I don’t care....I know why I said this....and what I meant.....just think...........would u wanna live in a peaceful world...or live in a world where only hate existed..  Btw....pls do not take this message in the wrong way I know there are many good people out there and I appreciate them for all the good things there are doing. And I am not trying to say that you are a bad person I swear I am not. I just want to point out that bcuz of a few bad mistakes we make we are marked for life....you are beautiful, talented and amazing! Your life does matter. You were brought into this world for a reason and that reason isn’t  to bring harm to ppl u don’t like or bring harm to yourself! Just know what ever you are going through it will get better and there are ppl who love you! ❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️

text: Not that I'm against this film, and love the title, revelations and cast in it, but the trailers reveal a repeat of a past, and in my opinion, poorly written plot device involving rebellion and the government stepping in as civilians, escalating things through their machinations to ensure carnage takes place. So it would seem, once again, out of better reception through the sequels, rather than the original, they are rinsing and repeating the same plot and characters. I am somewhat against this, as I enjoyed the original the most, which seemed much more psychological and realistic, before the government and all the anarchists and rebels took the plot over. However, I feel this is a disservice to the underplayed, but still original sequels. Further (..much like star wars...-_-) the original director of the first three films has been replaced in this addition by yet another director I've barely heard of and know little to nothing about, so he could be a straight up amateur..or a talentless..and relentless..producer..with political agendas for all I know. I still plan to see it but haven't decided when or how though with these mixed conceptions. I also wonder if people will attempt to copycat this film in anyway upon its release..so I will admit that adds a bit more realistic tension to it, as I somewhat fear in the distant future, such a program actually will be created, then made into a norm, then a holiday and even cultural value. As ridiculous as it sounds, the whole concept is even more disturbing than the matrix, skynet and AIs in this day and age...Careful friends, I'd recommend staying inside, but then again, you wouldn't be able to see the movie lols.

text: Serious question. Do non-whites feel like they're being pandered to with these kind of films, written in a way that amplifies any remnants of a victimization complex? I gotta pull out my gender card momentarily and say that I'm a woman, and I've gotten sick and tired of female leads being shoehorned into everything, especially in male-dominated genres. I hate it when a piece of media treats me like I have no self worth unless there's a woman there to construct a power fantasy for me. Do they really think I'm so apathetic that I can't identify with a story unless there's a chick holding the reins? Do they think my ego so ravenous that said female must compete with the men, out-competing them in many cases? I, for one, love it when the genders embrace their individual strengths and help one another overcome obstacles, not be pitted against or override each other.  In summary, I don't need my gender to be validated on the screen, so that's why I'm wondering if some people who aren't white see Hollywood for what I believe they are - self-aggrandizing elites fetishizing and profiting off of your identity. Any thoughts? (I haven't seen the film, so I'll accept the idea that my rambling might not be applicable to this movie. I was more-or-less inspired to write this after reading the comments, so feel free to treat this discussion as more of a general statement on modern media.)
